\pard\plain \ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Kant wrote the chapter on Schematism in his\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Critique_of_Pure_Reason"}{\fldrslt\f2\fs24\b0\i1 C}}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4 ritique of Pure Reason}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~to solve the problem of "...how we can ensure that categories have 'sense and significance.'\~ }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b1\i0 Whenever two things are totally different from each other, yet must interact, there must be some common characteristic that they share in order to somehow relate to one another. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 "\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85 an\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 a priori}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~concept which cannot, as it were, establish any empirical connections is a fraud \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85 the purpose of the Schematism chapter was to show that the categories at least do have satisfactory empirical connections."}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schema_(Kant)#cite_note-15"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0\super [15]}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~Kant was preoccupied "with bridging the otherwise heterogeneous poles of 'thought' and 'sensation' in the Schematism of the Pure Concepts of the Understanding (A 138/B 177)." }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs24\b1\i0 Phenomena}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  = objects }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 as they appear}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , structured by our forms of intuition and categories.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b1\i0 Noumena}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  = things\_in\_themselves, which }{\f1\fs24\b1\i0 cannot be known}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  because they lie outside the conditions of possible experience.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 "Intuitions," Kant wrote, "are always required to verify or demonstrate the reality of our concepts."}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schema_(Kant)#cite_note-Critique_of_Judgment,_%C2%A7_59-21"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0\super [21]}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~These examples ensure that "our abstract thinking has not strayed far from the safe ground of perception, and has possibly become somewhat high-flown or even a mere idle display of words."}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schema_(Kant)#cite_note-22"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0\super [}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 This is because "concepts are quite impossible, and are utterly without meaning or signification, unless an object is given for the concepts themselves, or at least for the elements of which they consist." }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Understanding is a protean concept in philosophy, and the desire for understanding is pervasive in everyday life. Scientists take it as their goal to understand the world and how it works, teachers and parents hope to transmit understanding to their students and children, and from a political and social point of view we often strive for mutual understanding. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~It then considers how the topic of understanding was lost and then \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93recovered\u8221\'94 in contemporary discussions in epistemology and the philosophy of science. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The ancient Greek word\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 episteme}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~is at the root of our contemporary word \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93epistemology\u8221\'94, and among philosophers it has been common to translate\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 episteme}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~simply as \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93knowledge\u8221\'94 (see, e.g., Parry 2003 [2020]).}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 For the last several decades, however, a case has been made that \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93understanding\u8221\'94 is a better translation of\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 episteme}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 . (For early influential arguments see, e.g., Moravcsik 1979; Burnyeat 1980, 1981; Annas 1981.) To appreciate why, note that knowledge, as now commonly conceived, can apparently be quite easy to get. }{\f1\fs24\b1\i0 Thus it seems I can know a proposition such as\~}{\f3\fs24\b1\i1 that it is raining outside}{\f1\fs24\b1\i0 \~just by opening my eyes. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It also seems that items of knowledge can be in principle isolated or atomistic. I can therefore apparently know that it is raining while knowing very little about other things, such as why it is raining, or what constitutes rain, or when it will stop}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Understanding seems to be different than knowledge in both respects. For one thing, understanding typically seems harder to acquire, and more of an epistemic accomplishment, than knowledge (Pritchard 2010). For another, the objects of understanding seem more structured and interconnected (Zagzebski 2019). Thus the subject matters we try to understand are often highly complex (quantum mechanics, the U.S. Civil War), and even when we try to understand isolated events (such as the spilling of my coffee cup), we typically do so by drawing connections with other events (such as the jostling of the table by my knee). }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 Complete knowledge subsumes the concept of understanding. Understanding is an attempt to organize the relations of bits of knowledge. But there would be no need to organize them if you could simply *see* it all happening simultaneously. If all apparent cause and effect is actively experienced, then there is no need for a concept called \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91relation\u8217\'92, and thus, no need for the attempt to understand them.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 As it is; What is the relationship between the rain, the clouds, and the oceans? From our limited perspectives, this is a puzzle; we experience the rain, we experience the cloud, we experience the ocean seperately as things in-and-of-themselves. As they occupy separate categories of things, we lack understanding about the relationship between them. We must *learn* and *discover* the relationships between these things, and once done, we bundle it all into a new thing we call the \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91climate;. The climate, then, stands in relation to other bundles of things; a creature; the sun; the molten core of the earth. But if you could see it all, experience it all simultaneously, you would have no need to learn about things, you would have no questions, the relationships between every bit would be experienced. The thing which can do this, this is god. This is omniscience.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Are there any experiences in which \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91understanding\u8217\'92}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Knowledge precludes understanding. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 A language without \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91be cause\u8217\'92}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Granted, what Greek philosophers had in mind by\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 episteme}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~often does not fully align with our contemporary ideas about understanding, because in the hands of philosophers such as Plato and Aristotle\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 episteme}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~is an exceptionally high-grade epistemic accomplishment. For Plato, full\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 episteme}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~seems to require a grasp of the basic elements of reality\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 in its most complete form, a grasp that traces back to the Form of the Good itself (Schwab 2016, 2020; Moss 2020). For Aristotle, it seems to require an appreciation of the deductive relationships that allegedly hold between natures or first principles and observable phenomena (Burnyeat 1981). In our contemporary use, by contrast, we often happily ascribe understanding to quite low-grade cases, where forms or first principles do not seem to be grasped or even relevant\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 as when we take ourselves to understand why the coffee cup spilled. Still, with its stress on systematicity and interconnectedness,\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 episteme}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~plausibly has more in common with our contemporary concept\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 understanding}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~than our contemporary concept\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 knowledge}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 . }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 If an understanding-like state was of fundamental epistemic importance to the Greeks, it is interesting to ask why the focus of epistemology shifted over time, and why an interest in knowledge, especially propositional knowledge, came to predominate\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 including and maybe especially quite isolated bits of propositional knowledge, such as\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 that I am sitting in front of a fire}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , or\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 that I have two hands}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 . }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Perhaps the shift occurred in response to the rise of scepticism in Hellenistic philosophy (Burnyeat 1980: 188; cf. Zagzebski 2001: 236). Or perhaps the modern focus on propositional knowledge was a response to the wars of religion in sixteenth and seventeenth century Europe, where it became increasingly important to distinguish good knowledge claims from bad, even with respect to quite isolated claims. (For more on the modern rise of interest in propositional knowledge, see Pasnau 2010; 2017.) Regardless of why the shift occurred, a desire to grasp \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93how things hang together\u8221\'94 undoubtedly remained a part of the human condition. It is therefore unsurprising that a move to revive understanding as a topic of philosophical inquiry eventually emerged. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 While the notion of understanding was often simply neglected in epistemology, in the philosophy of science it was for many years actively downplayed. A primary figure in this dynamic was Carl Hempel (see especially Hempel 1965). Although Hempel helped bring the notion of explanation back into respectability in the philosophy of science, he had significant reservations about tying explanation too closely to the notion of understanding.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Part of this seemed to stem from the fact that the idea of understanding that prevailed in his day was highly subjective and psychological\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 it emphasized more a subjective \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93sense\u8221\'94 of understanding, often tied to a felt sense of familiarity. As Hempel notes, however, poor explanations might excel along this dimension because they might}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 give the questioner a sense of having attained some understanding; they may resolve his perplexity and in this sense \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93answer\u8221\'94 his question.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93But\u8221\'94, he continues,}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 however satisfactory these answers may be psychologically, they are not adequate for the purposes of science, which, after all, is concerned to develop a conception of the world that has a clear, logical bearing on our experience and is thus capable of objective test. (Hempel 1966: 47\endash 48)}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The goodness of an explanation therefore seems to have little obvious connection to whether it manages to generate understanding in a particular audience. A good explanation might do that. But then again, it might not. Patently poor explanations are also able to generate a rich \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93sense\u8221\'94 of understanding in some audiences (think of conspiracy theorists), despite their shortcomings. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Philosophers such as Michael Friedman responded to Hempel\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s concerns by noting that simply because there seems to be a psychological element to understanding it does not follow that understanding is merely subjective or up for grabs (Friedman 1974). After all, knowledge has a psychological element, in light of the belief condition, but few hold that knowledge is merely subjective or up for grabs. Others, such as Jaegwon Kim, argued that leaving considerations about understanding out of accounts of explanation was deeply mistaken (Kim 1994 [2010]). After all, Kim claimed, we desire to explain things\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 because}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~we want to understand them. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Despite the efforts of Friedman, Kim, and others, significant reservations about the notion of understanding continued to linger in the philosophy of science (see, for example, Trout 2002). A notable shift occurred with Henk de Regt\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s distinction between the \u8220\'93feeling\u8221\'94 or phenomenology of understanding and genuine understanding (de Regt 2004, 2009: ch. 1; cf. de Regt and Dieks 2005). In particular, he argued that the feeling is neither necessary nor sufficient for genuine understanding. De Regt\u8217\'92s important distinction helped pave the way for a new surge of work on the topic over the last two decades, and helped philosophers move beyond thinking of understanding mainly in terms of felt \u8220\'93}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 aha!}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94 or \u8220\'93}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 eureka!}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94 experiences. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 As we look to particular accounts of understanding, it will help to consider in turn:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0\i0 a.	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 understanding\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s distinctive object (or objects),}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0\i0 b.	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 its distinctive psychology, and}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0\i0 c.	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 the distinctive sort of normative relationship that needs to hold between the psychology of the person who understands and the object of his or her understanding.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 By way of comparison, consider the traditional \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93justified true belief\u8221\'94 analysis of knowledge. On this view, knowledge involves a distinctive object (roughly, the truth, or a true proposition), a distinctive psychology (the psychological act of belief or assent), and a distinctive normative relationship that needs to hold between the psychology of the believer and the thing believed (namely, that one\u8217\'92s belief in the true proposition needs to be justified, in some sense).}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 What can be said, in a parallel way, about the elements of understanding?}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~let us start with the generic view that the objects of understanding are something like \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93connections\u8221\'94 or \u8220\'93relations\u8221\'94. Following a distinction from Kim (1994 [2010]), we can contrast two ways of thinking about these connections and relations\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 i.e., these plausible objects of understanding.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 According to\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 explanatory internalism}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , the connections or explanatory relations one grasps are \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93logico-linguistic\u8221\'94 relations that hold among a person\u8217\'92s beliefs or attitudes, or more exactly the contents of those beliefs or attitudes (Kim 1994 [2010]).\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 What}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~we grasp or see, when we understand some phenomenon, are how these various contents are logically or semantically related to one another.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Kim argues that Hempel is a paradigm example of an explanatory internalist (Kim 1994 [2010]; cf. 1999 [2010]). For instance, suppose that one wants to explain and hence understand why a particular bar of metal began to rust (McCain 2016: ch. 9). A good Hempelian explanation would be one in which a sentence describing the rusting follows inferentially from (a) a statement of the initial conditions (the moisture in the air, the constitution of the bar) and (b) a further law-like statement connecting the moisture, the constitution of the bar, and the onset of rust.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 This Hempelian framework seems internalist because what you see or grasp, when you understand the phenomenon, are connections among the propositions you accept\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 more exactly, you see or grasp different inferential or probabilistic connections among the contents of your beliefs that bear on the rusting. As Kim puts it:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 the basic relation that generates an explanatory relation is a logico-linguistic one that connects descriptions of events, and the job of formulating an explanation consists, it seems, in merely re-arranging appropriate items in the body of propositions that constitute our total knowledge at a time. In explaining something, then, all action takes place\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 within}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~the epistemic system, on the subjective side of the divide between knowledge and the reality known, or between representation and the world represented. (Kim 1994 [2010: 171\endash 172])}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 An\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 explanatory externalist}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~by comparison holds that the basic connections or relationship one grasps, when one understands, are not logico-linguistic but metaphysical. }{\f1\fs24\b1\i0 What you grasp, when you understand why the metal began to rust, are not primarily relationships among your beliefs or their contents. Rather, you primarily grasp real, mind-independent relationships that obtain in the world.}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Other epistemologists similarly point to coherence relations as the objects of understanding (e.g., Riggs 2003: 192). Since \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93coherence\u8221\'94 is presumably a relation that holds among the contents of beliefs, and not among items out there in the world, these views would qualify as internalist accounts of the objects of understanding, according to the Kimean framework. (For further examples and criticism, see Khalifa 2017a.) }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 a suggestion by Robert Nozick that}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b1\i0 explanation locates something in actuality, showing its actual connections with other things, while\~}{\f3\fs24\b1\i1 understanding}{\f1\fs24\b1\i0 \~locates it in a network of possibility, showing the connections it would have to other nonactual things or processes. (Nozick 1981: 12; cf. Grimm 2008)}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 understanding as  sort of generalized explanation}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Suppose in any case that the objects of understanding\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 the connections or relations we grasp when we understand\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 are out there in the world, and are not simply logico-linguistic items or elements of our psychology. According to a further important distinction from John Greco (2014), it does not follow that these logico-linguistic/psychological items\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 or more generally these\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 mental representations}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 do not play a crucial role in our coming to understand, because the representations typically play the role of\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 vehicles}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~of understanding, even if they are not themselves understanding\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s object. More generally, Greco notes, it is important to distinguish between the\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 object of understanding}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~vs. the\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 vehicle of understanding}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , i.e., \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93between the\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 thing}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~understood and its\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 representation}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94 (Greco 2014: 293). }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b1\i0 Appreciating the contrast between vehicle of understanding and object of understanding helps to reveal that in addition to pure internalist views about the object of understanding (where the objects of understanding are logico-linguistic relations), and pure externalist views (where the objects are worldly), there are also possible hybrid views. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b1\i0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 For instance, on the sort of view we find in Michael Strevens\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 Depth}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~(2008), what we grasp in the first instance are relations that hold among the contents of our beliefs: relations of deductive entailment or coherence or probabilistic support. This view is not simply internalist, however, because grasping these logico-linguistic relationships, and in particular the relationships of deductive entailment, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93mirror\u8221\'94 the real relationships that obtain in the world, and thus provide a vehicle for apprehending those relationships (Strevens 2008: 72). Thus Strevens holds that his theory is able to:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 show how a deductive argument, or similar formal structure, can represent causal influence\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85. When a deductive argument is of the right sort to represent a causal process that has as a consequence the state of affairs asserted to hold by the argument\u8217\'92s conclusion, I say that the argument\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 causally entails}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~the conclusion. A derivation that causally entails its conclusion, then, is one that can be used to represent (whether truly or not) a causal process that has the concluding state of affairs as its consequence. (Strevens 2012: 449)}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 On this view, by grasping or appreciating the necessitating force of an entailment relation one thereby grasps or appreciates the necessitating force of a causal relation\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 or, at least, something importantly like it.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 According to another hybrid approach, the internal logical or probabilistic relationships do not\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 mirror}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~the relationships out there in the world, but rather\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 provide evidence}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~for the existence of relationships out there in the world. Thus some hold that when things go well an appreciation or grasp of the probabilistic connections among the various things we believe allows us to infer the existence of real causal connections in the world (see}{\f1\fs24\b1\i0 \~S}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 pirtes, Glymour, & Scheines 1993; Pearl 2000 [2009]). As Wesley Salmon characterizes an earlier version of this idea,}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The explanatory significance of statistical relations is indirect. Their fundamental import lies in the fact\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85 that they constitute evidence for causal relations. (Salmon 1984: 192)}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 ultimately; you understand if you are able to predict. That is how you know you aren\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t dealing with purely logico-linguistic relations}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 you have no need of prediction if you know the future.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 With respect to the psychology of understanding, recall that the psychological element of propositional knowledge is typically construed in terms of\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 belief}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , where belief is taken to be a kind of assent or saying \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yes\u8221\'94 to the content of the proposition. Thus to believe that the sky is blue is to assent to the proposition\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 that the sky is blue}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 ; it is \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93taking it to be true\u8221\'94\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 that the sky is blue}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 .}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 When we turn to understanding, by contrast, some have claimed that a new suite of cognitive abilities comes onto the scene, abilities that we did not find in ordinary cases of propositional knowledge. In particular, some philosophers claim that the kind of mental action verbs that naturally come to the fore when we think about understanding\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93grasping\u8221\'94 and \u8220\'93seeing\u8221\'94, for example\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 evoke mental abilities \u8220\'93beyond belief\u8221\'94, i.e., beyond simple assent or taking-to-be-true (for an overview, see Baumberger, Beisbart, & Brun 2017).}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 For instance, Elgin, de Regt, and Wilkenfeld argue that those who grasp how things are connected are able to cognitively \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93do\u8221\'94 things that others cannot\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 they can apply their understanding to new cases, for example, and draw new inferences. (See, for example, Elgin 1996: 122\endash 24; de Regt 2004, 2017; Wilkenfeld 2013). Thus car mechanics who understand how engines work are able to make sense of engines that they have not encountered before, and to anticipate how changes in one part of the engine will typically lead (or fail to lead) to changes in other parts.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Grimm claims that the distinctive nature of these abilities flows from the distinctive nature of the objects of understanding (Grimm 2017). Suppose that the connections or relations one grasps are complex enough to constitute what we might call \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93structures\u8221\'94\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 structures with parts that depend upon one another in various ways. Arguably, for the mind to take up these structures in the right way, it is not enough simply to assent to their existence. Rather, one needs to appreciate how the structure \u8220\'93works\u8221\'94, or how changes in its various parts will lead, or fail to lead, to changes in other parts. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Finally, psychologists themselves have increasingly focused on characterizing the cognitive profile of understanding. Thus Tania Lombrozo and colleagues have explored the question of why we seek understanding, and how activities such as offering explanations aid in the acquisition and retention of understanding (Lombrozo, 2012; Williams & Lombrozo, 2010, 2013; Lombrozo & Wilkenfeld 2019). Psychologists have also explored the empirical question of how good (or bad) we are at identifying real relationships and dependencies in the world. According to Frank Keil, for example, we are not good at this at all, and we frequently fall prey to illusions of understanding (Keil 2006; cf. Ylikoski 2009). For instance, we often think we understand how a helicopter achieves lift,\~or how moving the pedals on a bicycle help to propel the bike forward.\~ But in both cases, we are often well wide of the mark (Keil 2006; cf. Grimm 2009; Sloman & Fernbach 2017). }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Is that all there is to understanding why your house burned down? Or does it also matter, for example,\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 how one comes to grasp}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~this relationship? These questions push us to ask about the normative dimension of understanding, and in particular to ask: Are there better and worse ways to come by one\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s grasp, and does this matter for the acquisition of understanding? For example, are careful experiments or good evidence needed? Or can one come by one\u8217\'92s grasp more or less by luck, and yet still in a way that generates understanding? }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 A parallel question with respect to knowledge would ask: Supposing you have a true belief, is that all there is to knowledge? And here most would say \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93no\u8221\'94. In addition to the true belief,\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 how you came by}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 that true belief}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~is also important. Is it based on good evidence, or a reliable process, or a well-functioning design plan? When it comes to knowledge, these further normative questions clearly matter. It is therefore not surprising that the same sorts of questions have been asked with respect to understanding.}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f1\fs24\b1\i0 For instance, suppose you read a history book full of inaccurate facts about the Comanche dominance of the Southern Plains in the nineteenth century, but your dyslexia miraculously transforms them all into truths (Kvanvig 2009). For Kvanvig, despite the one-in-a-billion luckiness of your grasp\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s origins, you could nonetheless come to an understanding of this topic. So long as the accuracy and internal appropriateness conditions are satisfied, how you came by your accurate grasp is not important.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs24\b1\i0 Other philosophers have objected to Kvanvig\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s account. On their view, it is implausible to think you can come to understand the world through sheer external luck, or (perhaps worse) through being the victim of massive deception (Grimm 2006; Pritchard 2010; Khalifa 2017b: ch. 7; Kelp 2021). Thus Pritchard claims that one needs to acquire one\u8217\'92s accurate grasp \u8220\'93in the right fashion\u8221\'94 (Pritchard 2010: 108) or \u8220\'93in the right kind of way\u8221\'94 (Pritchard 2010: 110)\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 in other words, by means of a reliable source or method. One\u8217\'92s grasp therefore cannot be the result of \u8220\'93Gettier luck\u8221\'94\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 where, for instance, by sheer chance a story intended to deceive you happens to be right (Pritchard 2010).}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 Thus Khalifa argues that attempts to revive understanding as a central notion in the philosophy of science have amounted to little more than a repackaging of existing models of explanation (Khalifa 2012, 2017b: ch. 3), and that strictly speaking all one needs for a plausible account of understanding is a plausible account of what counts as a good or correct explanation, combined with a plausible account of knowledge. Understanding therefore amounts to\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 knowing a correct explanation}{\f0\fs24\b0 . But then nothing new or special is needed to theorize about understanding; our accounts of explanation and our theories of\~knowledge do all the important theoretical work\~}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 between explanation and understanding:}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i1 Something\~E\~is an explanation of why\~Q\~only if someone who possesses\~E\~understands why\~Q}{\f0\fs24\b0 . (Skow 2018: 214)}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 This condition on explanation cannot help us as\~theorists, Skow argues, because it is not even true.\~Thus suppose we construe \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93possessing\u8221\'94 an explanation as\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 knowing}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~an explanation. Plugged into the formula, the result is that one cannot know an explanation of why\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 Q}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~unless that knowledge constitutes an understanding of why\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 Q}{\f0\fs24\b0 . But, plausibly, we can know an explanation of why\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 Q}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~without understanding why\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 Q}{\f0\fs24\b0 . For example, someone can know why the litmus paper turned red\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 because it was dipped in acid\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 without understanding why it turned red (Skow 2018: 215). This suggests it takes\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 more}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~to understand why p than simply to know why p. In the case of the litmus paper, Skow claims one also needs to appreciate\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 how}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~the acid turns the paper red, or\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 why}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~it turns it red.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 Opinions differ about the force of such examples. According to some, to require that understanding why p involves knowledge of mechanisms or deeper processes in this way would annihilate most of our everyday understanding (Grimm 2019a). Thus I can apparently understand why my eyes are watering\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 because I am chopping onions\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 without appreciating anything about the mechanism or connection that underlies the watering. Others argue that there is indeed understanding in these cases, although perhaps not a lot (Sliwa 2015).}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 A\~longstanding puzzle in the philosophy of science concerns how idealized models and\~representations (\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93idealizations\u8221\'94, for short) allow cognitive access to the world. The puzzle is that although idealizations seem to provide real epistemic benefits, the benefits cannot apparently be identified with truth, because to the extent that they falsify or mispresent the world, idealizations often fail to reflect the truth. For example, idealizations often appeal to entities that do not and perhaps cannot exist\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 fully rational agents, frictionless planes, etc. Or they subtract important worldly elements from their accounts\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 e.g., long range inter-molecular forces.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Yet if idealizations provide epistemic benefits, and we cannot readily think of the benefits in terms of truth, then how exactly should we think about them? According to some philosophers, we should think not in terms of truth but rather in terms of understanding. Understanding is the epistemic benefit we receive from idealizations, and understanding and truth can come apart. On this view, understanding (unlike knowledge) can therefore be \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93non-factive\u8221\'94 (Elgin 2004, 2017; Potochnik 2017; cf. Sullivan & Khalifa 2019).}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Yet if idealizations provide epistemic benefits, and we cannot readily think of the benefits in terms of truth, then how exactly should we think about them? According to some philosophers, we should think not in terms of truth but rather in terms of understanding. Understanding is the epistemic benefit we receive from idealizations, and understanding and truth can come apart. On this view, understanding (unlike knowledge) can therefore be \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93non-factive\u8221\'94 (Elgin 2004, 2017; Potochnik 2017; cf. Sullivan & Khalifa 2019).}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 For instance, Elgin asks us to consider a paint sample we might see in a hardware store\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 say, of the shade jonquil yellow (Elgin 2017: 187). While the sample might in fact be subtly different than the actual shade, and hence in that sense misrepresent it, it nonetheless seems to provide epistemic access to the shade. Idealizations such as the Ideal Gas Law or Snell\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s law work are then held to work in a similar way. They represent not by mirroring but rather by exemplifying certain aspects of the target system, and via the mechanism of exemplification enable understanding of the system (Elgin 2017).}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Others agree that idealizations enable scientists to understand the world even though, strictly speaking, the\~idealizations misrepresent their target systems. According to Angela Potochnik (2017), this is because the systems studied by scientists are enormously complex networks of causal patterns and interactions. Particular interests and cognitive limitations will lead scientists to focus\~on\~some of\~these\~causal patterns and neglect others, and they might get those particular patterns\~right. In the process, however, they will misrepresent the actual messy complexity of the target system, and the understanding of phenomena that results will thereby be non-factive.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 For Strevens, idealizations enable understanding because they draw attention to the differe}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 For Strevens, idealizations enable understanding because they draw attention to the difference makers that bring about the thing to be explained (Strevens 2017). More exactly, idealizations help us to appreciate the factors that make a difference to bringing about the phenomena we want to\~explain, and to identifying the factors that do not make a\~difference. The Ideal Gas Law helps us\~to\~understand the Boylean behavior of a gas, for example, even though the law imagines that there are zero long-range forces at work, because the existence of those long-rage forces does not make a difference to the derivation of the Boylean behavior: they are insignificant enough that their values can be set to zero without loss.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 the fundamental theory of population genetics; deviations from hardy-weinberg equilibrium;This model assumes random mating, no selection, no mutation, no migration, and infinite population size. It is the baseline against which evolutionary forces are measured. }
\par\plain 
\par\plain 
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \line }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 delightful. Coming to truth by sheer luck,}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 If you luckily rely on Source\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 X}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , that source can enable you to understand why the event occurred, even though it cannot generate knowledge about why it occurred, due to the presence of what Pritchard calls \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93environmental luck\u8221\'94. The upshot, on this view, is that while understanding is compatible with environmental luck, it is not compatible with Gettier luck. They conclude from this that since knowledge is compatible with neither Gettier luck nor environmental luck, understanding is not a species of knowledge.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 (For recent empirical studies regarding the compatibility of judgments of understanding with luck, and finding mixed support for this compatibility, see Wilkenfeld et al. 2018; Carter et al. 2019.)}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Gettier problem:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Attributed to American philosopher Edmund Gettier, Gettier-type counterexamples (called "Gettier-cases") challenge the long-held justified true belief (JTB) account of knowledge. The JTB account holds that knowledge is equivalent to justified true belief; if all three conditions (justification, truth, and belief) are met of a given claim, then there is knowledge of that claim. In his 1963 three-page paper titled "Is Justified True Belief Knowledge?",[1][2] Gettier attempts to illustrate by means of two counterexamples that there are cases where individuals can have a justified true belief regarding a claim but still fail to know it because the reasons for the belief, while justified, turn out to be false. Thus, Gettier claims to have shown that the JTB account is inadequate because it does not account for all of the necessary and sufficient conditions for knowledge.}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 All of these examples rely upon false premises, or conflation;}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 A fire has just been lit to roast some meat. The fire hasn't started sending up any smoke, but the smell of the meat has attracted a cloud of insects. From a distance, an observer sees the dark swarm above the horizon and mistakes it for smoke. "There's a fire burning at that spot," the distant observer says. Does the observer\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 know}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~that there is a fire burning in the distance?}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {- smoke is not smoke, but flies}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Also, Russel\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s example of time - Jane sees clock says 2 p.m.; she thinks it is 2 p.m. However, the clock only says 2 p.m. because it is stuck there. However, by chance, it is actually two p.m.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 - clock is not a working clock, but a broken one}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Dave sees a sheep in his field, but the sheep is only a dog dressed up as a sheep. Dave believes there is a sheep in his field, and is correct because, unbeknown to him, there is a real sheep hidden in a defelade.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 - sheep is not a sheep, but a dog dressed up as a sheep.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 as more general Gettier-style problems were then constructed or contrived in which the justified true belief is said to not seem to be the result of a chain of reasoning from a justified false belief. For example:}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 After arranging to meet with Mark for help with homework, Luke arrives at the appointed time and place. Walking into Mark's office Luke clearly sees Mark at his desk; Luke immediately forms the belief "Mark is in the room. He can help me with my logic homework". Luke is justified in his belief; he clearly sees Mark at his desk. In fact, it is\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 not}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~Mark that Luke saw, but rather a hologram, perfect in every respect, giving the appearance of Mark diligently grading papers at his desk. Nevertheless, Mark\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 is}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~in the room; he is crouched under his desk reading\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gottlob_Frege"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 Frege}}{\f0\fs24\b0 . Luke's belief that Mark is in the room is true (he is in the room, under his desk) and justified (Mark's hologram is giving the appearance of Mark hard at work).}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 It is argued that it seems as though Luke does not "know" that Mark is in the room, even though it is claimed he has a justified true belief that Mark is in the room, but it is not nearly so clear that the\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 perceptual belief}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~that "Mark is in the room" was inferred from any premises at all, let alone any false ones, nor led to significant conclusions on its own; Luke did not seem to be reasoning about anything;"Mark is in the room" seems to have been part of what he\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 seemed to see}{\f0\fs24\b0 .}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 this seems deeply unsastifactory, because \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91mark in is in the room\u8217\'92 is a seeming; but if it were on the table that holograms were real, this seeming would be: mark or mark\u8217\'92s hologram is in the room.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {But epistemic justification doesn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t require eliminating all logically possible alternatives. It requires only that the seeming is }{\f0\fs24\i1 good enough}{ evidence in normal circumstances.}
\par\plain {Even if holograms exist, Luke is still justified in believing Mark is present, because:}
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 One response, therefore, is that in none of the above cases was the belief justified because it is impossible to justify anything that is not true. Conversely, the fact that a proposition turns out to be untrue is proof that it was not sufficiently justified in the first place. Under this interpretation, the JTB definition of knowledge survives. This shifts the problem to a definition of justification, rather than knowledge.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 This account of justification is supported by philosophers such as\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Boghossian"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 Paul Boghossian{\f0\fs24\b0\super [}{\f0\fs24\b0\super 20]}}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rHTYzyzRt70"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 [1]}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~and\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stephen_Hicks"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 Stephen Hicks}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://web.archive.org/web/20141222000209/http://www.stephenhicks.org/wp-content/uploads/2009/10/hicks-ep-full.pdf"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 [2]{\f0\fs24\b0 [3]}}}{\f0\fs24\b0 . In common sense usage, an idea can not only be more justified or less justified but it can also be partially justified (Smith's boss told him X) and partially unjustified (Smith's boss is a liar). Gettier's cases involve propositions that were true and believed, but which had weak justification.\~}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \~In common sense usage, an idea can not only be more justified or less justified but it can also be partially justified (Smith's boss told him X) and partially unjustified (Smith's boss is a liar). Gettier's cases involve propositions that were true and believed, but which had weak justification. In case 1, the premise that the testimony of Smith's boss is "strong evidence" is rejected. The case itself depends on the boss being either wrong or deceitful (Jones did not get the job) and therefore unreliable. In case 2, Smith again has accepted a questionable idea (Jones owns a Ford) with unspecified justification. Without justification, both cases do not undermine the JTB account of knowledge.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 From a pragmatic viewpoint of the kind often ascribed to James, defining on a particular occasion whether a particular belief can rightly be said to be both true and justified is seen as no more than an exercise in\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pedant"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 pedantry}}{\f0\fs24\b0 , but being able to\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decision_making"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 discern}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~whether that belief led to fruitful outcomes is a fruitful\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Action_(philosophy)"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 enterprise}}{\f0\fs24\b0 . Peirce emphasized\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fallibilism"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 fallibilism}}{\f0\fs24\b0 , considered the assertion of absolute certainty a barrier to inquiry,}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gettier_problem#cite_note-22"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [{\f0\fs24\b0\super 22]}}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~and in 1901 defined truth as follows: "Truth is that concordance of an abstract statement with the ideal limit towards which endless investigation would tend to bring scientific belief, which concordance the abstract statement may possess by virtue of the confession of its inaccuracy and one-sidedness, and this confession is an essential ingredient of truth."}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gettier_problem#cite_note-23"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [{\f0\fs24\b0\super 23]}}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~In other words, any unqualified assertion is likely to be at least a little wrong or, if right, still right for not entirely the right reasons. Therefore, one is more veracious by being Socratic, including recognition of one's own ignorance and knowing one may be proved wrong. This is the case, even though in practical matters one sometimes must act, if one is to act at all, with a decision and complete confidence.}{ }
\par\plain 
